Name: Lucas Horn

xv6 Project 1B - Process Info, Blocking, and Resource Usage
=============================================================

Modified files
--------------
  kernel/proc.h
  kernel/proc.c
  kernel/trap.c
  kernel/syscall.h
  kernel/syscall.c
  kernel/sysproc.c
  kernel/defs.h
  user/usys.pl
  user/user.h


Description of changes
----------------------

Task 1 - getprocinfo:
  Added sys_getprocinfo() in kernel/sysproc.c. It calls myproc() to get the
  current process, fills a local proc_info struct with p->pid, p->parent->pid,
  p->state, and p->sz, then uses copyout() to send it to user space. If
  p->parent is null it just sets ppid to 0.

  struct proc_info is defined in both kernel/proc.h and user/user.h with the
  same layout so copyout() transfers it correctly. No locking needed since a
  process cant race with its own syscall, and we're running CPUS=1.

  Wired it up in kernel/syscall.h (SYS_getprocinfo = 22), declared the extern
  and added it to the syscalls[] table in kernel/syscall.c, and added the
  entry in user/usys.pl plus the declaration in user/user.h.

Task 2 - blockchild / unblockchild:
  Rather than adding a new value to the main procstate enum and touching
  everything that checks it, I added a separate state_extra field to struct
  proc in kernel/proc.h using a new enum procstate_extra with values BLOCKED
  and UNBLOCKED. Its initialized to UNBLOCKED in both proc.c:allocproc() and
  proc.c:freeproc().

  The scheduler in proc.c:scheduler() just got one extra condition - it skips
  any process where state_extra == BLOCKED, everything else stays the same.

  I also updated proc.c:wakeup() to not transition a BLOCKED process from
  SLEEPING to RUNNABLE. Without this, a sleeping child that gets blocked could
  get woken up by an unrelated wakeup() call, and then when you unblock it
  theres no wakeup coming to actually get it running again.

  blockchild() and unblockchild() are at the bottom of kernel/proc.c since
  they need direct access to the proc[] array. Both scan the table, grab
  p->lock, verify the target is a direct child of the caller and is in a
  valid state (not UNUSED, USED, or ZOMBIE), then flip state_extra. Trying
  to double-block or double-unblock returns -1.

  sys_blockchild() and sys_unblockchild() wrappers are in kernel/syscall.c,
  they just call argint() to get the pid argument then call blockchild() or
  unblockchild(). Syscall numbers SYS_blockchild = 23 and
  SYS_unblockchild = 24 added to kernel/syscall.h.

Task 3 - getresourceusage:
  Added 4 counter fields to struct proc in kernel/proc.h: cpuTicks,
  syscallCount, contextSwitches, sleepCount. All zeroed in proc.c:freeproc().

  Where each one gets incremented:
    - cpuTicks: in trap.c:usertrap() when which_dev == 2 (timer interrupt)
    - syscallCount: in trap.c:usertrap() when r_scause() == 8 (syscall),
      incremented before syscall() is dispatched
    - contextSwitches: in proc.c:scheduler() right before the swtch() call,
      after the process is selected and set to RUNNING
    - sleepCount: at the top of proc.c:sleep(), before acquire(&p->lock)

  sys_getresourceusage() is in kernel/sysproc.c. It calls myproc(), copies
  the 4 counter fields into a local resource_usage struct, uses copyout() to
  send it to user space, and returns p->pid. struct resource_usage is defined
  in both kernel/proc.h and user/user.h. Syscall number SYS_getresourceusage
  = 25 in kernel/syscall.h.


Testing
-------
  Used user/procmon.c (provided with the assignment) to test all three tasks
  together. It forks a child that prints every 5 ticks, blocks it, waits 10
  ticks to confirm the child goes silent, then unblocks it. After that the
  parent runs a heavy workload to drive up the resource counters and prints
  the final getresourceusage() output. Also used it to verify getprocinfo()
  returns correct pid, ppid, state, and memory size at the start.

  Some output lines had parent and child printf mixed together (like
  "ParenChild (4): running...") which is just xv6 having no stdout locking,
  not a bug.


Known limitations
-----------------
  - Everything assumes CPUS=1 per the project instructions. The counter
    increments arent atomic so this would break on multiple CPUs.

  - syscallCount is incremented before syscall() runs so it counts the
    invocation regardless of whether it succeeds. Seemed like the right
    interpretation of "each invocation counts once".

  - proc_info and resource_usage are defined in both kernel/proc.h and
    user/user.h. If one changes the other has to be updated manually, thats
    just how xv6 handles the kernel/user split.